# Guest kernel **determinism overlay**, merged LAST (after the vendored Kata
# guest-kernel config in kata/) via scripts/kconfig/merge_config.sh, then
# olddefconfig — so every entry here WINS over Kata's container-host base.
# Task 36 rebased the base from `tinyconfig` to Kata's config (capability:
# cgroup-v2/overlayfs/ext4/namespaces/... for tasks 37/38); this overlay is
# unchanged in intent — it only configures out the nondeterminism Kata's base
# turns on (SMP, dynticks, KASLR, CPU-freq, HW-RNG, PM timer, ...). Determinism
# is enforced from below (patched KVM + V-time + the VMM device models); this
# overlay governs capability/probe surface only. Comment discipline: every entry
# says why it is here. Symbols marked "(overrides Kata =y)" flip a value the Kata
# base sets the other way — build-kernel.sh asserts each survives the merge.

## Identity / build determinism
# 64-bit kernel (ARCH=x86_64 forces it; pinned to document intent).
CONFIG_64BIT=y
# Non-relocatable kernel, KASLR impossible: load addresses must never vary.
# (overrides Kata base.conf CONFIG_RELOCATABLE=y and x86_64/base.conf
# CONFIG_RANDOMIZE_BASE=y. The cmdline also passes nokaslr. RANDOMIZE_BASE-off is
# the load-bearing determinism lever and is asserted; RELOCATABLE-off is best-
# effort — it is not asserted in case a base symbol re-selects it, since a
# relocatable-but-not-randomized kernel still loads at the loader's fixed GPA.)
# CONFIG_RELOCATABLE is not set
# CONFIG_RANDOMIZE_BASE is not set
# Empty version suffix and no git-describe: git state must not leak into the
# binary (reproducibility lever from the task spec).
CONFIG_LOCALVERSION=""
# CONFIG_LOCALVERSION_AUTO is not set
# gzip (not xz) for the kernel image: in-kernel gzip is deterministic and it
# is one fewer host tool whose version can change the bytes.
CONFIG_KERNEL_GZIP=y
# CONFIG_KERNEL_XZ is not set

## CPU / topology
# SMP=y (kept from the Kata base) so the cpuset cgroup-v2 controller exists â k3s/
# kubelet hard-require it. maxcpus=1 keeps exactly ONE online vCPU (the determinism
# lever: no second CPU to race or IPI); the VMM exposes a single vCPU regardless.
# Documented IMPLEMENTATION.md follow-on (CPUSETS), determinism re-validated via r2.
CONFIG_SMP=y
# SCHED_MC_PRIO (Intel Turbo-Boost-Max core ordering; default y under SMP) is meaningless
# on a single vCPU and `select`s CPU_FREQ + X86_INTEL_PSTATE (a select overrides a plain
# "not set") â disable it so the cpufreq stack (a non-determinism source) stays off.
# CONFIG_SCHED_MC_PRIO is not set
# Single deterministic memory domain. (overrides Kata x86_64/numa.conf CONFIG_NUMA=y.)
# CONFIG_NUMA is not set
# No frequency scaling: timing must not drift with governors. With SMP=y the x86
# cpufreq DRIVERS meet their deps and pull CPU_FREQ back on, so disable the drivers
# too. (overrides Kata cpu.conf CONFIG_CPU_FREQ=y + perf governor and
# x86_64/acpi.conf CONFIG_ACPI_CPU_FREQ_PSS=y.)
# CONFIG_X86_INTEL_PSTATE is not set
# CONFIG_X86_ACPI_CPUFREQ is not set
# CONFIG_X86_PCC_CPUFREQ is not set
# CONFIG_X86_AMD_PSTATE is not set
# CONFIG_ACPI_CPU_FREQ_PSS is not set
# CONFIG_CPU_FREQ is not set

## Time
# Periodic ticks at a fixed low rate — no dynticks machinery deciding when
# the next tick is; the hypervisor will deliver ticks deterministically.
# HZ_PERIODIC=y wins the "Timer tick handling" choice, so NO_HZ_COMMON (the
# dynticks machinery, which selects TICK_ONESHOT) and Kata's CONFIG_NO_HZ_FULL=y
# (x86_64/base.conf) are both off. Kata's deprecated CONFIG_NO_HZ=y (base.conf)
# harmlessly survives — it only sets the choice *default* and selects nothing once
# HZ_PERIODIC is chosen. build-kernel.sh asserts HZ_PERIODIC=y and
# NO_HZ_COMMON/NO_HZ_FULL/NO_HZ_IDLE/TICK_ONESHOT off after olddefconfig.
CONFIG_HZ_PERIODIC=y
CONFIG_HZ_100=y
# No high-resolution timer reprogramming; the periodic tick is the timer.
# (overrides Kata base.conf CONFIG_HIGH_RES_TIMERS=y.)
# CONFIG_HIGH_RES_TIMERS is not set
# TSC is the only fine-grained clocksource "where possible": the ACPI PM
# timer is configured out here; HPET support cannot be (CONFIG_HPET_TIMER is
# def_bool y on x86-64, no prompt), so the HPET is kept out at runtime
# instead — the hypervisor will simply not expose one, and the boot gate
# passes -machine hpet=off (alternative: the hpet=disable boot parameter).
# CONFIG_X86_PM_TIMER is not set
# The harmony paravirt work-derived clock (task 110, docs/PARAVIRT-CLOCK.md
# §3.1): a clocksource + sched_clock whose read path is a seqlock page load —
# never a raw counter read. The source is added by patches/apply-guest-patches.py
# before the config merge. Compiled in but RUNTIME-INERT without the
# harmony_pvclock kernel parameter (which only the vmm appends when it offers
# the page), so this image boots byte-for-byte as before everywhere else and
# one image serves as both the page-on and page-off measurement arm. When
# active it marks the TSC unstable, closing the kernel-timekeeping raw-RDTSC
# path (the RDTSC trap stays underneath as the backstop for everything else).
CONFIG_HARMONY_PVCLOCK=y

## Entropy / randomness
# No hardware RNG drivers — entropy must come from our hypercall channel.
# (overrides Kata virtio-extras.conf CONFIG_HW_RANDOM=y / HW_RANDOM_VIRTIO=y;
# the latter is dropped by olddefconfig once HW_RANDOM is off.) RDRAND is trapped
# to the seeded stream by the patched backend; the cmdline also passes
# random.trust_cpu=off so RDRAND entropy is never credited at boot.
# CONFIG_HW_RANDOM is not set
# (CONFIG_RANDOM_TRUST_CPU was removed in kernel 6.2: RDRAND crediting is the
# random.trust_cpu= boot parameter now — default on, so the boot gate passes
# random.trust_cpu=off — and RDRAND itself is trapped by the hypervisor.
# Nothing to set at build time in 6.18.)

## Memory management
# No THP/KSM daemons rewriting page tables on their own schedule.
# CONFIG_TRANSPARENT_HUGEPAGE is not set
# CONFIG_KSM is not set

## Power states
# The guest never sleeps or hibernates; poweroff is the only transition.
# CONFIG_SUSPEND is not set
# CONFIG_HIBERNATION is not set
# ACPI so `poweroff -f` actually powers the (QEMU) machine off and the boot
# gate can observe QEMU exiting. PCI is required with it: QEMU's DSDT
# declares PCI config-space operation regions, and without the PCI region
# handler ACPICA fails table load (AE_BAD_PARAMETER) and never registers
# pm_power_off.
CONFIG_ACPI=y
CONFIG_PCI=y

## Kernel/userspace surface the image actually needs
# Everything is built in; no module loader, no runtime code variability.
# CONFIG_MODULES is not set
# printk + 8250 serial console: the only output channel (console=ttyS0).
CONFIG_PRINTK=y
CONFIG_TTY=y
CONFIG_SERIAL_8250=y
CONFIG_SERIAL_8250_CONSOLE=y
# Run /init: a #!/bin/sh script invoking a static ELF busybox.
CONFIG_BINFMT_ELF=y
CONFIG_BINFMT_SCRIPT=y
# Boot from the external gzip initramfs; no other decompressors compiled in.
CONFIG_BLK_DEV_INITRD=y
CONFIG_RD_GZIP=y
# CONFIG_RD_BZIP2 is not set
# CONFIG_RD_LZMA is not set
# CONFIG_RD_XZ is not set
# CONFIG_RD_LZO is not set
# CONFIG_RD_LZ4 is not set
# CONFIG_RD_ZSTD is not set
# /proc, /sys, /dev for the init script.
CONFIG_PROC_FS=y
CONFIG_SYSFS=y
CONFIG_DEVTMPFS=y
# Baseline syscall surface a static-glibc busybox expects.
CONFIG_FUTEX=y
CONFIG_POSIX_TIMERS=y
# Block layer + real filesystems: KEPT from the Kata base (do NOT disable). Task
# 36's whole point is a container-class kernel: tasks 37/38 need a RAM-backed
# block device + real ext4 + real fsync (BLOCK / BLK_DEV_LOOP / BLK_DEV_RAM /
# EXT4_FS), plus overlayfs/cgroup-v2/namespaces — all provided by kata/. The old
# `# CONFIG_BLOCK is not set` / `# CONFIG_EXT4_FS is not set` lines were removed
# here: merged last, they would have overridden Kata and cascade-disabled the
# entire container capability. None of block/ext4/overlayfs is a determinism risk
# (no wall-clock, no host RNG — backed by RAM in 37/38), so the overlay leaves
# them on. See the capability audit in guest/linux/IMPLEMENTATION.md.
# Userspace port-I/O privilege syscalls (iopl/ioperm) for the in-guest workload
# agents' hypercall doorbell (task 86 first box smoke, 2026-07-09: the
# allnoconfig seed leaves iopl(3) ENOSYS, so play-agent — and flow-agent, whose
# doorbell has the identical latent dependency — cannot ring OUT 0x0CA1 from
# userspace). Interim capability until R-L3's /dev/harmony driver retires
# userspace port I/O for applications (docs/LAYERS.md). Determinism-neutral:
# syscall availability changes nothing unless called, and the doorbell OUT is
# the same deterministic port exit the VMM already services; the task-86
# campaign 25/25 replay gate re-validates the rebuilt kernel. Asserted in
# build-kernel.sh so a Kata-side regression cannot silently drop it.
CONFIG_X86_IOPL_IOPERM=y
# /dev/mem itself (same smoke, next layer down): the doorbell transport maps
# the two fixed hypercall pages (REQ 0xE000 / RESP 0xF000 — reserved out of
# the guest's e820, deliberately) out of /dev/mem, and the allnoconfig seed
# ships no CONFIG_DEVMEM at all ("/dev/mem: No such file or directory").
# Same interim status and determinism argument as IOPL above; STRICT_DEVMEM
# stays off (the mapped pages are reserved, not kernel RAM). Asserted.
CONFIG_DEVMEM=y
